<article id="post-3802" class="post-3802 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry category-general tag-agnostic tag-athlete tag-catholic tag-non-political tag-spanish tag-tennis-player">
    
	<div class="entry-content">
  
		<div id="ingrown-sidebar" role="complementary">
			<aside id="hollowverse_summary_widget-2" class="widget widget_hollowverse_summary_widget"><div class="hollowverse-summary">
  <h2>Religion</h2>
  <p>Nadal was raised a Catholic, but now calls himself an agnostic. </p>
  <h2>Political Views</h2>
  <p>Nadal isn't political, but does contribute to making the world a better place through his foundation. </p>
</div>
      </aside>		</div><!-- #secondary .widget-area -->
    
		<p>Rafael Nadal, whose full name is Rafael Nadal Parera, was born and raised in Manacor, Majorca, Spain.</p>
<p>Being a Spaniard, it is natural that Nadal <span style="color: #ff0000;"><span style="color: #000000;">would come</span></span> from a Catholic tradition, which he does. But he says he doesn&#8217;t practice the faith anymore.<sup><a href="#footnote_0_3802" id="identifier_0_3802" class="footnote-link footnote-identifier-link" title="Tennis&rsquo; Holiest: Roger Federer &ndash; The Godsend: Looking at Some of the Best Roman Catholic Athletes. The Bleacher Report.">1</a></sup></p>
<p>Nadal is more of an agnostic these days. During an interview, in which Nadal was directly asked if he believes in God and what he thinks about athletes who cross themselves during game play, he said:</p>
<blockquote><p>It&#8217;s hard to say, &#8216;I don&#8217;t believe in God.&#8217; I would love to know if God exists. But it&#8217;s a very difficult thing for me to believe. I don&#8217;t know. It&#8217;s private and I don&#8217;t want to speak about it, but I say, &#8216;If God exists, you don&#8217;t need [to cross yourself] or pray.&#8217; If God exists, he&#8217;s intelligent enough to [do] the important things, the right things.<sup><a href="#footnote_1_3802" id="identifier_1_3802" class="footnote-link footnote-identifier-link" title="Rafael Nadal discusses history, Wimbledon, definition of glory. Sports Illustrated.">2</a></sup></p></blockquote>
<p>Apparently, Nadal just counts on his skill, athleticism, and hard work to win tennis matches.
<div class="middle-ad"><script type="text/javascript"><!--
google_ad_client = "ca-pub-8989100382265388";
/* THV mid ad */
google_ad_slot = "3196775548";
google_ad_width = 336;
google_ad_height = 280;
//-->
</script><script type="text/javascript"
src="https://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/show_ads.js">
</script></div>
<h2>Politics of an international athlete</h2>
<p>In the sense that politics is the business of mainstream governance, Nadal isn&#8217;t too involved. <span style="color: #000000;">But </span>there seems to be a lot of pride in his family for their home-island of Majorca. When Nadal was offered a chance as a teenager to play tennis in Barcelona, his father declined, saying:</p>
<blockquote><p>I donâ€™t want to believe that you have to go to America, or other places to be a good athlete. You can do it from your house.<sup><a href="#footnote_2_3802" id="identifier_2_3802" class="footnote-link footnote-identifier-link" title="At Home With Humble Yet Ambitious Nadal. Inside Tennis.">3</a></sup></p></blockquote>
<p>Nadal has been affected by the world&#8217;s problems. He says, as a result of his success, that he &#8220;owes&#8221; society and has started a charitable foundation to start paying back. The foundation, called the Rafa Nadal Foundation, aims to use athletics to help young people in destitute situations in developing countries, to rise above their plight. He said:</p>
<blockquote><p>This can be the beginning of my future, when I retire and have more time&#8230; I am doing very well and I owe society&#8230; A month-and-a-half ago I was in Chennai, in India. The truth is we live great here [in Europe]. I can contribute something with my image.<sup><a href="#footnote_3_3802" id="identifier_3_3802" class="footnote-link footnote-identifier-link" title="Rafael Nadal launches foundation, &ldquo;I am doing very well and I owe society,&rdquo; says Rafa. Down the Line Tennis Blog.">4</a></sup></p></blockquote>
<p>Other than that, Nadal is just involved in the sordid world of tennis politics.</p>

